<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: War rages for Treasury's ear
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THESE ARE heady days for Westminster backbenchers. After years as
inconsequential makeweights, an anaemic government majority and the presence
of Maastricht at the top of the political agenda, have contrived to give
them a modicum of real power.
Mr John Townend, the Conservative MP for Bridlington, demonstrated this
emphatically over the weekend, when he took the government unawares by
predicting on BBC television that there would be intense pressure to devalue
sterling if the economy was not showing signs of recovery by the beginning
of next year.
A majority of Tory MPs would now favour a general realignment of the
exchange rate mechanism, said Mr Townend, whose prime source of influence is
as chairman of the Tory backbench finance committee, to which he was
recently elected, seeing off a challenge from Sir David Mitchell, a former
transport minister.
In this capacity, he will routinely represent Conservative backbench views
on the economy, being guaranteed the ear of the Treasury team whenever he
requires it.
His election has widely been regarded as evidence of a drift to the right
within the parliamentary party.
The presence in such a position of this outspoken and staunchly Thatcherite
Euro-sceptic will at least be helpful to chancellor Norman Lamont and his
Treasury colleagues in one key respect. He is as convinced as they are of
the importance of keeping spending under control. 'I strongly believe in a
balanced budget,' he says, remarking on the additional strain under which
falling Treasury revenues are putting public finances.
But his stance on interest rates may contribute to an uneasy second half for
Mr Lamont if the economic news does not improve.
In the continued absence of 'green shoots', a bluntly delivered message to
the effect that lower interest rates were necessary to kick-start a recovery
might come from Mr Townend - a successful small businessman - as soon as
November.
If achieving this meant engineering an upward revaluation of the D-Mark or
even ditching the exchange rate mechanism, this Hull-born wine merchant and
hotelier would shed few tears - as his weekend comments made clear.
He expresses doubt, however, that a unilateral rejection of the ERM would
actually achieve the desired objective. Britain is 'really hog-tied' to the
mechanism, he says, lapsing into the Humberside argot with which his
conversation is peppered: Bridlington is probably the only British
constituency in which pigs outnumber people.
A provincial Tory squire of the old school, Mr Townend holds the sort of
views on non-fiscal issues you might hear voiced a hundred times over at
Conservative party conference.
In favour of restoring capital punishment, he was one of 11 Tories to oppose
the government's 1990 bill to allow residence for 50,000 Hong Kong families.
'I was certainly representing the views of my constituents,' he says.
He is one of the true believers who still argue that the newly-elevated
Baroness Thatcher would have beaten off Mr Michael Heseltine's challenge had
she opted to run in the second Tory leadership ballot.
Among his less trumpeted achievements, Mr Townend is credited by Mr John
Prescott, the Labour deputy leadership candidate, with smoothing his path to
Westminster when Mr Prescott first contested the Hull East seat 22 years
ago.
As the Labour frontbencher recalls, popular disenchantment with local
housing policies adopted during Mr Townend's stint on Hull city council
helped him home with a comfortable 22,000 majority.
The defeated Tory candidate on that occasion was one Norman Stewart Hughson
Lamont.
Mr Tim Collins, press minder to Mr John Major during the general election
campaign, has been appointed Tory party director of communications,
succeeding Mr Shaun Woodward.
Mr Tim Smith, Tory MP for Beaconsfield, becomes a party treasurer in
succession to Lord Beaverbrook, and Mr Tony Garrett succeeds Sir John Lacy
as head of campaigning.
</TEXT>
