<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Senior Tories angry at committee
ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT last night ran the gauntlet of bitter criticism from some of
its most senior backbenchers as it succeeded in excluding its bete noire Mr
Nicholas Winterton from membership of the parliamentary select committees
which monitor its affairs.
After a noisy and bad-tempered debate, an amendment that would have
reinstated Mr Winterton, the Tory MP for Macclesfield, as a member of the
health select committee which he chaired until the election was defeated by
63 votes (147-210).
His exclusion followed a ruling by government business managers to the
effect that no Conservative MP could serve on a committee for more than
three consecutive parliaments.
The ruling also hit Sir John Wheeler, the scrupulously loyal Conservative MP
for Westminster North who had been a member of the home affairs select
committee since its inception in 1979.
An amendment effectively permitting Sir John's exclusion was carried by the
narrower margin of 21 votes (160-139).
An angry Mr Winterton took his revenge by accusing the government of 'an
arrogance that can lead to dictatorship.' 'An independent view and freedom
of speech is being gradually squeezed out in this House,' he said.
He was supported in his clear resentment of the government's elaborate
efforts to check parliament's right to scrutinise the executive both by Sir
John and Mr Terence Higgins, former Tory chairman of the Treasury and civil
service select committee.
Sir John likened the three-term rule to the experience of stepping on a
piece of bubble gum - 'tacky, sticky and lingers long after the event.'
Mr Higgins claimed that the rule had been 'invented at the last moment in
order justify a particular series of selection.'
In a direct attack on Sir Marcus Fox, the Tory MP widely credited with
masterminding the government's tactics, Mr Higgins said there was 'no such
rule' about the time an MP could serve.
Sir Marcus's rule was also condemned by Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of
the social security select committee in the last parliament, who said it
would 'deskill' the committee system.
Opening the debate, Sir Marcus, chairman of the committee of selection,
sought amid much heckling to justify the decision to exclude long-serving
committee members. 'There are many good reasons why we should say that 13
years is long enough,' he said.
</TEXT>
