<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Scots may export water to England
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND may join other rainy areas of Britain in exporting water to
southern England to relieve the water shortage on a long-term basis, a
government minister revealed yesterday.
Mr Allan Stewart, the Scottish industry minister, said the Scottish Office
was examining a scheme drawn up by the construction industry for
transporting water from the southern uplands of Scotland. He said the
project would cost 'at least four figure millions' - at least Pounds 1bn -
and would be an important boost to Scotland's construction industry.
This is the first time Scotland has been mentioned as a possible source to
boost southern England's water supply. Up to now only Northumbria, Cumbria
and Wales have been considered. The issue is politically sensitive in
Scotland as it follows an announcement last week by Mr Ian Lang, Scottish
secretary, that was widely seen as paving the way for privatisation of water
north of the border.
Mr Lang said he was appointing consultants to consider 'alternative forms of
organisation for water and sewerage services, including ways in which the
private sector might contribute enterprise and investment.' Water in
Scotland is the responsibility of the regional councils, but with these
likely to be abolished in the forthcoming Scottish local government
reorganisation the question of how water will be organised in future has to
be addressed.
It is understood that a Scottish-based construction company has drawn up a
scheme to transport water from rivers and existing reservoirs in the
southern uplands to England by means of pipelines and tunnels. The plan
would not involve the creation of reservoirs - which would require the
flooding of valleys.
The scheme depends on changes to laws preventing water sale between Scottish
regional councils and presumes that Scottish water will be privatised.
</TEXT>
