<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Rafidain Bank wins reprieve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN APPLICATION by the Bank of England to wind up Rafidain Bank, the Iraqi
state-owned bank whose UK branch is in provisional liquidation, was delayed
for another year in the High Court in London yesterday.
Sir Donald Nichols, the vice-chancellor - the senior judge of the Chancery
division - ruled that in view of the continued freeze on Iraqi assets since
the invasion of Kuwait in 1990, the application should be adjourned until
the first day of the Trinity legal term in 1993.
He also approved a plan for the creation of a nine-person creditors'
committee to liaise with the two partners at Price Waterhouse appointed as
provisional liquidators last year.
The Bank requested that Rafidain be placed in provisional liquidation on
February 21 last year. It argued that this would prevent a worldwide
scramble for the assets held in the UK branch of the bank.
The London branch of Rafidain is the only branch outside the Middle East.
Other branches within Iraq and the Middle East continue to trade.
The High Court was asked at a previous hearing to consider whether it had
the powers to wind-up a foreign, state-owned bank. Representatives of the
various interests in the case decided at the time that no further action
could be taken until a change in the political circumstances between the UK
and Iraq.
Sir Donald said yesterday that in the 'very unusual circumstances'
surrounding the status of the bank, 'the justification of the last 12 months
still holds good'.
The court was told that if Rafidain was placed in liquidation now, the
dividend to creditors would be less than one half of one pence in the pound.
A further deferment would be in the creditors' interest.
The creditors' committee will include the Deposit Protection Board, an Iraqi
creditor and up to seven other creditors including four of the largest who
are willing to serve.
Goodman International and Anglo Irish Beef Processors, two Irish beef
producers, agreed not to serve on the committee. As joint creditors for more
than Pounds 100m, they are taking legal action to recover their assets.
Separately, a circular from Price Waterhouse distributed to creditors last
month shows that the liquidators had been notified of worldwide assets in
Rafidain totalling Pounds 260m, against liabilities of Pounds 4.68bn by the
end of April this year.
The assets include Pounds 163.7m held in London and Pounds 96.3m overseas
about which the liquidators have been notified. Its liabilities in London
are Pounds 125.9m and those overseas Pounds 4.5bn.
</TEXT>
