<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / BCCI creditors' appeal case opens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM LAWRENCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of individual creditors of the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce
International yesterday appealed against last month's High Court ruling that
sanctioned a Dollars 1.7bn (Pounds 885m) compensation package. The package
was negotiated between Touche Ross, the liquidators, and the bank's Abu
Dhabi majority shareholders.
The legal move follows the decision of the British creditors' committee not
to appeal when it was told that it might be liable for costs in the action
rather than being able to recover any appeal costs from BCCI assets.
Mr David Hunt QC, counsel for the creditors, argued in the Court of Appeal
that Sir Donald Nicholls, the vice-chancellor who approved the compensation
package, had wrongly substituted his own commercial judgment for that of the
creditors.
The creditors' committee voted to recommend rejection of the deal by a 7-1
majority.
Sir Donald, giving judgment last month, said the proposals, which will give
creditors between 30 per cent and 40 per cent of their original investments,
represented the best option for the bank's 140,000 creditors in 70
countries.
Mr Hunt argued that the wishes of the majority of the creditors should be
paramount. 'Creditors can be expected to be the best judges of where their
own financial interests lie,' he said.
The creditors are headed by Dr Adil Elias, chairman of the BCCI Depositors
Protection Association, who claims to be a creditor for Pounds 1m.
He is supported in the appeal by the trustees of Film and Photo Design
Pension Fund, the Faisal Islamic Bank of Egypt and nine individual
Jordanian-based creditors. All will be at risk on costs if the appeal fails.
The hearing is expected to last until tomorrow.
</TEXT>
