<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Decay eats away at inner cities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIFTEEN YEARS of govern-ment initiatives have done 'surprisingly little' to
improve life in deprived inner cities, a Policy Studies Institute report
concludes today.
The report acknowledges that the most recent schemes - City Challenge and
the establishment of an Urban Regeneration Agency - have not yet had time to
prove themselves.
It says, however, that 'given the record so far, it is difficult to have
much confidence in more of the same or to feel at all hopeful about the
future prospects for deprived urban areas'.
Without more money and sound management, concludes the report, trends in
deprived areas will 'continue to disappoint the hopes of residents and the
aspirations of government'.
If no increase in government resources is possible, it urges redirection of
other funds to the most deprived parts of the country.
The PSI, a leading independent economic and social policy research
institution, bases its report on official statistics since 1977, when the
then Labour government published the white paper Policy for the Inner
Cities. This sought to reduce disadvantage in inner-urban areas.
It concludes that, while there have been some improvements, the gap between
deprived areas and the rest of the country in general remains as wide as it
was 15 years ago.
'In some respects the gap has widened,' says the report.
Its findings include:
The worsening of pupil-teacher ratios - against the national trend - in most
of the deprived local education authority areas studied. In general there
had been a worsening in examination achievements in deprived areas compared
with the rest of England.
With the exception of the north-west, fewer people from deprived areas than
expected were on Employment Training schemes.
People from deprived areas were more likely to remain unemployed after
leaving Employment Training and Youth Training schemes, with no evidence of
improvement in this position over time.
The proportion of families in poverty - measured in terms of those
qualifying for social security benefits - had grown. Premature death among
adults remained greater in deprived areas than elsewhere. While there had
been improvements in infant mortality rates throughout the country, most
deprived areas still had records that were worse than the national average.
Estate Action and other housing programmes had not resulted in
home-improvement and renovation schemes ing a higher priority in deprived
areas than elsewhere. The decrease in social housing meant that little new
low-cost property had been built to help ease the housing difficulties of
deprived areas.
While unemployment fell in a third of deprived areas between 1983 and 1991,
it had remained the same or increased in the other two thirds.
During the 1980s, says the report, grants from central government to local
authorities declined in real terms.
Although most deprived areas had lost proportionately less grant than other
locations, the bulk of recent available funding had gone to urban
development corporations, with London Docklands receiving the lion's share.
Spending on the mainstream urban programme in England outside development
corporation areas had declined in real terms during the 1980s.
'The decay at the heart of Britain's cities is one of the biggest challenges
faced by its government,' says the report.
Successive administrations had been trying to reverse negative trends by
stimulating environmental renewal, encouraging investment, creating jobs and
attempting to give residents a better quality of life.
The institute's conclusions are based on 36 urban areas which scored the
highest on the Department of Environment's deprivation indicators. These
indicators consider the extent of factors such as unemployment, overcrowded
homes and lack of amenities.
The report acknowledges that there is a 'fundamental difficulty' involved in
establishing the causes of the trends which it identifies. It was not
possible to tell whether, without the initiatives taken in the inner cities
during the past 15 years, the gaps between deprived areas and the rest of
the country might have grown still wider.
It also recognises that some innovative measures have been introduced only
recently. It had been suggested, says the report, that City Challenge -
under which local authorities compete for funding for specific schemes -
would focus resources more effectively and encourage local partnerships.
Likewise, in two years' time the proposed Urban Regeneration Agency might
have shown its effectiveness.
'There is something in all these points. Even so, the conclusion to which
our analyses lead is disturbing.'
Urban Trends 1. Policy Studies Institute. Bookshops or BEBC Distribution,
Post Office Box 1496, Poole, Dorset BH12 3YD. Pounds 19.95.
