<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Blue Arrow trial unfair court told
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FOUR City advisers convicted of fraud over the Blue Arrow scandal were
denied a fair trial because of the length and complex nature of the legal
proceedings and the judge's late decision to cut down the case against them,
the Court of Appeal was told yesterday.
Mr Jonathan Cohen, a former County NatWest chief executive, Mr David Reed, a
former head of corporate finance at County and Mr Nicholas Wells, a former
County director, were all given 18-month suspended sentences at the end of
the trial which lasted a year and four days. Mr Martin Gibbs, a former head
of corporate finance at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, received a one-year suspended
sentence.
All four men were convicted of conspiring to mislead the markets over the
result of the 1987 Blue Arrow rights issue by secretly buying shares
themselves to raise the take-up level announced to other investors.
All except Mr Wells were in court yesterday to hear Mr Anthony Hooper QC
open the appeals against their convictions.
'The weight, length and complexity was such that a fair trial was not
possible,' he told the three appeal court judges, Lord Justice Mann, Mr
Justice Buckley and Mr Justice Ognall.
The decision of the trial judge, Mr Justice McKinnon, to dramatically reduce
the size of the case against the four men after all the evidence had been
heard, and both prosecution and defence closing speeches made, was a
'material irregularity' in the proceedings, he continued.
During pre-trial hearings, defence lawyers had continually argued that the
prosecution's case was too large and would result in an unmanageable trial.
However, the prosecution had insisted that the case could not be cut back
and that the trial would last only between four and six months, Mr Hooper,
for Mr Reed, said.
Half-way through the trial the judge had said the prosecution had lost sight
of the limits of the jury system but that its case could not then be cut
back further. Later, in his summing-up he restricted the case to just the
'late take-up' issue, telling the jury to ignore 75 per cent of the
evidence. The evidence that remained had mostly been given at the start of
the year-long trial, Mr Hooper said.
Mr Vivian Robinson QC, for Mr Wells, said that in not cutting back the size
of the trial before it began, the judge had made a fundamental error from
which all other mischiefs followed.
It would be naive not to think the jury would be influenced by the months of
evidence they had heard but were later told to disregard, Mr Robinson said.
The appeal is expected to last between one and two weeks.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
