<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Careers Service is urged to raise its profile
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CAREERS Service should consider launching a campaign to raise its
profile among employers, according to a report by the Institute of Manpower
Studies.
A survey of 2,200 employers showed that while the majority knew the service
existed, a much smaller proportion used it on a regular basis.
Only half of the employers who were active in the young persons' labour
market were involved with the service. The report says that if companies
knew more about the service and how it could assist them they might consider
using it.
Use was greatest among larger employers and manufacturing companies and
least among smaller companies and the service sector.
Those companies that did use the service were generally happy with it, most
using it as a junior Jobcentre to find young people to interview. In a
number of these cases the local service provided the additional service of
pre-selecting people.
It was in such screening that the survey encountered the highest level of
dissatisfaction among employers, with complaints about the inappropriateness
of the people put forward.
Some employers said they wanted to see the Careers Service expanding the
element of its activities aimed at the adult workforce. A small percentage
said they would be willing to pay for services such as aptitude testing and
potential assessment of their employees.
IMS Report No 222, IMS, Mantell Building, University of Sussex, Falmer,
Brighton BN1 9RF. Pounds 30.
</TEXT>
