<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Lautro warns on pension switches
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW RULES to be announced later this week will warn sales agents from life
insurance companies against encouraging members of occupational pensions
schemes to switch to personal pensions.
A draft of the document by Lautro, the self-regulatory body for the life
insurance industry, says that the rules are likely to mean that after an
analysis of each potential client's situation, 'many' will be advised not to
make a purchase.
Personal pensions have been among the most significant sources of new
business for the life insurance industry, accounting for 39 per cent of all
new business underwritten in the year to March 31.
Lautro is to release an enforcement bulletin for sales agents because,
according to a draft document, it is concerned 'that adequate care was not
always being taken by company representatives in establishing whether or not
it was bona fide in the interests of members of occupational pension schemes
to transfer to personal pension plans'.
Mr Brian Sharp, secretary to the Association of British Insurers' Life
Council, said he believed the rules were already best practice within the
industry and were unlikely to cause a stir.
Mr Ron Spill, pensions manager at Legal and General, said the rules embodied
what was already followed at his company and would not force any change in
practice.
However, Lautro has noted a sharp rise in complaints from the public of
high-pressure sales tactics used to encourage workers to leave attractive
employer-sponsored schemes. For this reason it decided to make new rules.
Occupational schemes offer many benefits that personal pensions cannot -
such as additional contributions from employers, inflation-adjusted benefits
and survivors' benefits for death in service. Those who transfer out of
occupational schemes often receive lump sums worth far less than benefits
they would have been entitled to had they stayed in the scheme, even if they
had switched to a new employer and stopped contributing to the original
scheme.
The draft rules also suggest that companies receiving complaints from those
who have been urged to transfer out of an employers' scheme into a personal
pension scheme should consider whether the new guidelines were followed when
the sale was made.
In addition, the rules seek to limit the amount of commission that can be
charged to clients up-front.
Life insurance companies typically deduct up to two years premiums to pay
sales costs on long-term insurance contracts.
The new rules will limit commissions on personal pensions to a percentage of
each year's premium - typically 4 per cent to 5 per cent.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
