<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Names' leader to head new agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR DAVID Berriman, a prominent City figure and a leader of loss-making
Lloyd's Names, is to head a new agency at the troubled insurance market.
Sir David, a former merchant banker who holds a range of directorships, will
chair the agency - which has been formed by a merger between two smaller
groupings, Knightstone and Spratt &amp; White.
He is the latest of a number of Names - individuals whose assets support
underwriting at Lloyd's - to take a more active role in the management of
the market's businesses.
Sir David has assumed prominence at Lloyd's as chairman of the Rose Thomson
Young Action group, formed by Names who are members of Syndicate 255.
This syndicate ran up heavy losses as a result of its involvement in spiral
reinsurance, in which syndicates and companies reinsure each other's
exposures to catastrophe losses.
Sir David said: 'A lot of the failures of Lloyd's in the past have been
linked to the failure of managing agents to manage underwriters. We will
watch our syndicates like hawks.'
In a separate development the High Court will today hear a motion from
Lloyd's seeking to set aside a motion calling for a judicial review of the
market's authorities.
Six Names connected to the Gooda Walker Action group initially sought the
judicial review in May.
Judicial reviews are actions against public or semi-public bodies which are
alleged to have failed to observe their - often statutory - duties.
Meanwhile, Lloyd's confirmed yesterday that voting on the resolutions being
put forward at the society's extraordinary general meeting on 27 July will
be by postal ballot.
</TEXT>
