<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Home loans face threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDING SOCIETIES may have to cut lending to first-time buyers because of
pressure from insurance companies, the chief executive of a leading building
society warned yesterday.
Mr Martin Armstrong, head of Norwich &amp; Peterborough Building Society, said
insurance companies were trying to impose terms on mortgage-indemnity
insurance that would depress the market.
'There is a strong likelihood that the maximum percentage on loans we can
offer borrowers will be reduced from 95 per cent to 90 per cent, harming the
first-time-buyer market,' Mr Armstrong said.
Insurers have been renegotiating contracts with mortgage lenders since the
end of last year.
Most existing contracts for mortgage-indemnity insurance, a one-off payment
insuring high loan-to-value mortgages, finish on August 31.
Insurance companies have made heavy losses in the mortgage indemnity
business in the last two years because of the squeeze on the housing market
and the fall in house prices.
Royal Insurance, one of the market leaders, faces losses of more than Pounds
400m from domestic mortgage indemnities.
It says it is trying to develop a proper trading relationship with its
clients.
Legal &amp; General, another large insurer, said it had stopped dealing with
several small building societies to concentrate on larger lenders.
Two small societies, Buckinghamshire and Kent Reliance, confirmed yesterday
that Legal &amp; General had told them it would no longer offer them
mortgage-indemnity insurance.
Both say their experience of bad loans has been very low and they are
negotiating with other insurance companies.
Mr John Wriglesworth, a housing market analyst at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, said
the insurance companies were operating a cartel in dealing with mortgage
lenders.
'All the new terms for the contracts are exactly the same wording,' he said.
'The insurance companies risk shooting themselves in the foot.'
</TEXT>
