<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Unease at universities' pay deal signalled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Education confirmed yesterday that it has convened a
meeting with university vice-chancellors and the Association of University
Teachers which almost certainly indicates government displeasure at the pay
deal that was agreed for university teachers in May.
The AUT and the vice-chancellors agreed a 6 per cent rise with a further 1
per cent to be distributed locally later in the year. With the delay in
implementing the award the AUT says the increase to the salary bill is about
5.75 per cent.
However, with the government keen to restrict public-sector pay rises to 4
per cent - as it did last week for the 2,000 top civil servants covered by
the Top Salaries Review Body - the lecturers' rise is regarded by ministers
as eating up too much of the overall university grant. By threatening to
alter the level of the overall grant the government is in a strong position
to force a reduction in the pay rise.
An AUT spokeswoman said that since 1979 average non-manual earnings have
risen 58 per cent in real terms while academic earnings have risen only 10
per cent.
Some vice-chancellors had indicated during the negotiations with the AUT
that they could not afford a pay rise higher than 2 per cent. However, the
AUT said that those universities with special difficulties had been taken
into account in the negotiations.
The House of Lords yesterday reserved judgment in a test-case appeal that
will decide whether senior university lecturers can count on keeping their
jobs until retirement without fear of being made redundant on cost-cutting
grounds.
Five law lords headed by Lord Keith heard 4 1/2 days of legal argument in an
appeal by Professor Edgar Page, a 61-year-old philosophy lecturer made
redundant by Hull University in October 1988.
The law lords' decision is not expected before the start of the new legal
year in October.
</TEXT>
