<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / New Delhi defied over Hindu temple
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR S B Chavan, the Indian home minister, said yesterday the Uttar Pradesh
government had defied a directive from India's highest court by permitting
the start of construction of a Hindu temple near the site of a 16th-century
mosque at Ayodhya, located in the state.
Mr Chavan, who was forced to make a statement in the house, ruled out the
possibility of an immediate action against the right-wing Hindu Bharatiya
Janata Party (BJP) whose government had flouted the ruling of the courts,
saying that 'the final decision of the Supreme Court would have to be
awaited.' BJP is the largest opposition group in the Indian parliament.
Last week, the supreme court admitted a writ petitioning against the
construction. A hearing is set to begin this week.
Hindu militants began building the temple last week, reopening a dispute
which has led to more than 2,000 deaths during the past three years. The
issue has been dormant for the past six months.
Mr Chavan, who visited Ayodhya at the weekend, told a noisy house that he
had offered Mr Kalyan Singh, the state chief minister, more security to
ensure that the disputed land was not encroached upon, but Mr Singh declined
the offer.
Paramilitary forces guarding the ancient Babri Masjid mosque have been
watching helplessly as hundreds of Hindu devotees continue to pour into the
town they believe is the birthplace of the god, Ram.
The Supreme Court had directed the central government and the Uttar Pradesh
chief minister to 'maintain status quo' in the disputed complex on November
15 last year.
Opposition parties accused the government of having no concrete plan to stop
the violation of the court order by Mr Singh's state government, which had
overtly allowed the construction to begin, amid elaborate rituals.
The BJP, which has used the temple issue to become the largest opposition
party at the centre and to wrest power in Uttar Pradesh, accused other
opposition parties of 'playing with the sentiments' of the minority Moslem
community.
Mr Ram Vilas Paswan of the opposition's Janata Dal party, demanded the
resignation of the Narasimha Rao government because it had failed to stop
construction on the disputed site and had therefore 'violated the
constitution'.
MPs earlier yesterday cast votes - all but 14 of the 710 members voted  - in
the tenth presidential elections to choose a successor to Mr Ramaswamy
Venkataraman. Counting will begin on July 16, and a new president named on
July 25.
</TEXT>
