<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Pound falls to post-poll low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POUND fell yesterday to its lowest level against the D-Mark since the
day before the general election amid growing expectations that the German
Bundesbank would tighten monetary policy this week.
International investors ignored a strong statement by Mr John Major, the
prime minister, ruling out a devaluation of the pound, selling sterling in
large quantities and buying D-Marks.
The government insisted it would hold sterling's position against the D-Mark
in the European exchange rate mechanism even if other European governments
forced a realignment. But it could not halt a sharp fall in sterling's
value.
The foreign exchange markets were unmoved by Mr Major's promise to bring
down UK inflation 'to nil if possible'.
Instead they bid the D-Mark higher against most leading currencies following
reports that this week's meeting of the Bundesbank council was likely to act
to curb the strong growth in German money supply.
Sterling fell two pfennigs to DM2.8525 in London before dipping in late
trading to DM2.8489, a level last seen on April 8 when the market was
troubled at the prospect of a Labour victory in the general election. The
German currency gained against the dollar, which dropped 1.75 pfennigs to
DM1.478, and hit a 15-month high against the Japanese yen. In New York, the
pound closed at DM2.84 and Dollars 1.9295.
Unmoved by criticism from some Tory backbenchers, Mr Major said: 'It is
absolutely imperative that we do not duck the necessity of bringing
inflation down to a level below that of our competitors, as low as we can
get - to nil if possible - and seek to keep it there.'
The ERM, he added, provided the cornerstone of that policy.
Further cuts in rates would be linked to holding sterling's parity.
'When it is appropriate we reduce interest rates,' he said. 'It has to be
when it's appropriate - when we can sustain the exchange value of sterling
and still reduce interest rates.'
His remarks were later expanded by Downing Street to emphasise that the
prime minister regarded sterling's present central rate of DM2.95 as
non-negotiable.
Officials made clear that if other governments wanted to devalue against the
German currency, Mr Major would insist that the pound was held at DM2.95.
Speculation about a general realignment has been fuelled by intervention to
support the Italian lira. There are signs that the Bundesbank would regard a
realignment as an appropriate move for ERM countries that thought they were
suffering from German monetary policy.
But with France adamantly opposed to any devaluation of the franc, Britain
sees little prospect of a general realignment. In Brussels, Mr Piero
Barucci, Italy's new finance minister, said there was 'no consideration' of
devaluing the Italian lira.
EC economics and finance ministers, in Brussels for one of their regular
council meetings, expressed concern about Europe's high interest rates but
conceded that the level of rates was effectively in the hands of the
Bundesbank.
Members of the Bundesbank council will discuss on Thursday whether to raise
the German discount rate from 8 per cent or to limit the ability of
commercial banks to borrow from the German central bank against collateral
at the Lombard rate. Ministers in Brussels appeared to believe the
Bundesbank would not raise rates this week.
In a letter to The Times today, six leading monetarist economists, including
Lady Thatcher's former personal economic adviser, Sir Alan Walters, warn of
'the serious risk that the present slump . . . will be deepened and
prolonged well into 1993 and beyond'. They criticise Mr Lamont's defence of
the ERM as 'brave but misguided'.
The six argue: 'Leaving the ERM for a properly constructed regime of
money-supply targets would certainly permit interest rates to drop
substantially below German rates. . . The pound would perforce fall, and
rightly so.'
