<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / OFT chief hints at action to regulate CD prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Bryan Carsberg, the newly appointed director-general of fair trading,
has raised the possibility of instituting regulatory action over the high
price of compact discs just three months after his predecessor rejected the
idea.
In a letter last week addressed to Mr Nigel Griffiths, a Labour frontbench
consumer affairs spokesman, Sir Bryan said he wanted to 'review the evidence
personally' before deciding on whether a case 'exists for additional work
and perhaps formal regulatory action'.
Mr Griffiths wrote to Sir Bryan last month requesting a new inquiry, saying
the investigation by Sir Gordon Borrie, the previous director-general, had
left consumers feeling dissatisfied.
Sir Gordon said at the beginning of April that an inquiry by the Office of
Fair Trading had found no evidence of collusion between record companies and
retailers.
Compact discs were more expensive than cassette tapes and vinyl records and
this could not be explained by differences in production costs, Sir Gordon
said.
He made clear, however, that CD prices were high because consumers were
willing to pay more for them. 'In other words, the prices of CDs have
settled around a level which, on the whole, the market appears willing to
bear.'
He added: 'There appears to be no action the office could take to stimulate
a sharper degree of price competition than our inquiries now suggest
prevails, however beneficial such competition might be to consumers.'
In his letter to Mr Griffiths, Sir Bryan, who took up his post last month,
says: 'There are some indications that the price of compact discs is higher
than it should be but the evidence so far is not clear-cut, and the
identification of causes of excessive prices, in the structure of the
industry, is difficult.'
The OFT said yesterday that Sir Bryan would examine the evidence already
collected before deciding whether further investigations should be carried
out.
</TEXT>
