<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / International Company News: Promotion and research hold down
net at Intel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEL, the leading US semiconductor manufacturer, yesterday reported an 8
per cent drop in second-quarter net income as heavy marketing and investment
programmes ate into record revenues.
The company, which is facing increasing competition from chip 'cloners' such
as Advanced Micro Devices, has been spending heavily on advertising to set
itself apart from the crowd on a new generation of chips.
Intel reported net income of Dollars 213m, or Dollars 1 a share, compared
with Dollars 231m, or Dollars 1.10, in the second quarter of last year.
Revenues rose 5 per cent from Dollars 1.25bn to Dollars 1.32bn. The figures
were broadly in line with market expectations.
For the first quarter of this year, Intel produced net income of Dollars
184m, or 86 cents a share, on revenues of Dollars 1.24bn.
It said business conditions were strongest in the US and Europe. Japan and
the Asia-Pacific region, which had been relatively sluggish in recent
quarters, improved from first-quarter levels.
It said its overall microprocessor business was 'quite strong' in the second
quarter, particularly in its newer products.
Revenues from the company's older 'first wave' 386 DX and SX chips continued
to decline as a result of the personal computer market's switch to more
powerful 'second wave' systems.
Revenues of standard semiconductor products and system-level products
exceeded expectations for the quarter. The book-to-bill ratio for the period
exceeded 1.0.
