<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Civil servants to strike over proposed move to Docklands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TENSIONS over government plans to move civil servants to Docklands were
highlighted yesterday, as Downing Street pressed departments to look again
at whether more officials can be relocated and civil service unions decided
to stage a one-day strike tomorrow in protest at any move.
The Downing Street initiative is understood to stem from dissatisfaction on
the part of Mr John Major, the prime minister, at government departments'
paltry responses to a preliminary survey of what activities they might shift
to Docklands.
Despite organised coach trips for staff to the site to try to reduce
resistance to the move, the strike votes show that many officials remain
strongly opposed to going to Docklands because of the extra cost and time
they will face in travelling to work.
The 2,000 civil servants in the Department of the Environment are the only
officials definitely signed up to move to Docklands, though there is also
strong pressure on the Department of Transport, which is carrying out a
review of its office requirements, and the Department of Trade and Industry.
So far, the DTI has volunteered only the Radio Communications Agency.
The strike is part of a growing campaign among officials against the move
away from the area round Westminster.
It will coincide with a lobby of parliament tomorrow, when the issue is also
expected to be raised during questions to environment ministers in the
Commons. DoE union leaders are to meet Mr Michael Howard, the environment
secretary, on Friday.
At the DoE, members of the NUCPS civil service union, which represents
middle-ranking staff, voted 60 per cent in favour of strike action while 62
per cent of members of the CPSA union, which represents junior officials,
were in favour of striking.
At the transport department, members of NUCPS voted 55 per cent in favour of
strike action.
The FDA and IPMS civil service unions, which represent senior and
professional staff, support the Westminster lobby but are not taking part in
the industrial action.
Mr John Delaney, NUCPS group secretary, said: 'Although it is a one-day
strike called at very short notice because parliament is adjourning for
three months, we intend to campaign throughout the summer.'
'Our members are not going to Docklands, to a place where there is no
infrastructure and inadequate transport. It is a political decision because
they cannot persuade their friends in the private sector to take up the
space.'
</TEXT>
