<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / High Court sets aside judgment against Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE REPUBLIC of Iraq has succeeded in having a judgment for more than
Dollars 500m (Pounds 260m) set aside by the High Court in London. The
judgment was obtained against it last year by Kuwait Airways Corporation.
In a ruling given in April, but only just made public, a judge in the
Commercial Court held that KAC's writ was not validly served. The writ was
served through diplomatic channels on the Iraqi Embassy in London in January
last year, with a request that it be forwarded to the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs in Baghdad.
However, Mr Justice Evans said service on a state was deemed to have been
effected when a writ was received by its foreign ministry and there was no
evidence that the KAC writ was received by the ministry in Baghdad.
The judge rejected a claim by Iraqi Airways Company, against which KAC has a
judgment for nearly Dollars 490m, that the writ was not validly served on
it.
He also rejected IAC's arguments that it had state immunity from KAC's legal
action and that the English court did not have jurisdiction to deal with the
dispute.
Yesterday KAC's London solicitor, Mr Christopher Gooding, of Clyde &amp; Co,
said Iraq had won only 'a Pyrrhic victory' because the writ would eventually
be validly served on it.
The case concerns 10 KAC airliners which, after the invasion of Kuwait, were
flown to Iraq and handed over to IAC.
Six of the aircraft were later flown to Iran, where they were interned by
the Iranian authorities. The other four aircraft were destroyed in air raids
on Iraq.
In January last year KAC started legal proceedings in London and obtained
judgment for Dollars 515,274,988 damages against Iraq and Dollars
489,455,380 against IAC, neither defendant having taken part in the
proceedings.
The judgments were stayed last July when IAC and Iraq gave notice that they
wanted to contest KAC's claim and intended claiming state immunity and
challenging the High Court's jurisdiction to deal with the dispute.
</TEXT>
