<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 92 / International Company News: KIO deflects blame over Ercros
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUWAIT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KUWAIT'S main investment body yesterday responded to claims that it had
mismanaged a multi-billion dollar investment portfolio in Spain by leaking a
lengthy defence of its actions to the official Kuna news agency, Reuter
reports from Kuwait.
An 'official source' at the Kuwait Investment Office (KIO) blamed other
investors for the collapse of a chemicals company, Ercros, in its portfolio,
and said KIO was happy to pay out a Pounds 100m Eurobond if nervous
investors demanded it.
It was the first official response to reports that the KIO, known as one of
the world's most powerful investors, may lose hundreds of millions of
dollars and damage its international credibility through the partial
collapse of its Spanish portfolio, put at about Dollars 7bn.
Western diplomats and economists say the KIO's worldwide portfolio may have
sunk to below Dollars 40bn from a pre-Gulf war total of about Dollars 100bn.
At some stages in the 1980s, Kuwait was earning more from investments than
from its oil exports.
Kuwaiti investment officials in Kuwait have declined to comment. The
al-Watan newspaper reported yesterday that the KIO's deputy chairman, Mr
Khaled al-Sabah, had tended his resignation but it had not so far been
accepted.
KIO's Spanish portfolio has come under scrutiny after Ercros announced 10
days ago it was due to file for court protection on its Dollars 302m debt.
Ercros' bankruptcy allows investors in a Pounds 100m bond issued by the
KIO's main investment vehicle in Spain, Grupo Torras, to redeem the bond
early, which would be a serious setback to the Kuwaiti fund's reputation.
In the statement to Kuna, a senior unnamed official said the KIO was trying
to negotiate with the Spanish government and Spanish creditors to share
responsibility for refloating Ercros, which the KIO had borne alone in the
past.
'Torras is obviously sorry that one of the companies it holds shares in
could reach this stage . . . but in the end it considers itself an investor
looking for profit and avoiding loss,' the official said.
</TEXT>
