FT  13 JUL 92 / Paint sales point to low industrial activity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SALES OF paint
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
one of the more certain indicators of industrial activity - plunged in May
and June, suggesting that a significant economic upturn may not be evident
before next year, Ian Hamilton Fazey writes.
The Paintmakers Association annual conference in Torquay at the weekend
heard that an uplift in sales in the first quarter of this year was a false
dawn. Figures have not yet been collated, but companies described May sales
as 'grim' and those in June as 'dire'.
If the economy falters and fewer things are being made, paint sales dip,
usually faster than gross domestic product, as manufacturers stop buying and
use up stocks. Conversely, recovery sees paint orders pick up at a faster
rate than GDP as restocking takes place alongside growth.
The conference was also told that some companies have needlessly committed
themselves to extra costs by pre-empting environmental law.
The standards are for emissions of volatile organic compounds - mainly
solvent from industrial paints and coatings - and are to be enforced by 405
councils. If a company commits itself to tighter controls than those
required by law, it must adhere to them and cannot revert to legal limits.
</TEXT>
