<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 92 / Financial services expect upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE financial services sector may be about to pick up, according to a report
published today. However, it warns that business volumes remain well below
normal and says that improved profitability has been won partly through job
losses and reduced costs.
For the only the second time since December 1989, the report - prepared
jointly by the Confederation of British Industry and accountants Coopers &amp;
Lybrand - records an upturn in business confidence.
According to the 333 companies surveyed, business confidence in many UK
financial services strengthened in the second quarter of the year, even
though business levels remained well below normal.
There was also a slight rise in business volumes during the quarter, the
first since June 1990. Total operating costs were down for the third quarter
in succession.
The most optimistic financial services are general insurance, fund
management, venture capital and finance houses, but banking and building
societies still report a weakening in their confidence.
Less than a third of financial services companies expect business volumes to
rise in the quarter now under way, and only 4 per cent think there will be a
drop in business.
The survey says that uncertainty about business prospects is still holding
back investment plans and that spending by financial services companies on
information technology over the next year looks like falling for the first
time since the survey began.
Companies are planning to curb spending on land, buildings, vehicles, plant
and machinery in the drive to control costs. They are also cutting spending
on staff training.
With operating costs down and wider margins on their business, the
profitability of companies surveyed is expected to rise still further over
the next three months.
In the life insurance sector, business volumes are still depressed and
expectations of a recovery have been unfulfilled. The CBI says companies
that sell products through brokers fared markedly better than those which do
not.
Building societies were among the sectors that did worse, with demand
shrinking and no signs of improved margins or fee income.
CBI/Coopers &amp; Lybrand Financial Services Survey No 11. CBI Economic Trends
Department, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford Street, London WC1A 1DU. Pounds 31.
</TEXT>
