<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 92 / Ford unions in Europe join forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS representing Ford workers across Europe are combining forces for the
first time to make representations to the company.
They believe Ford management in the US has taken a strategic decision to
sub-contract an increasing number of production processes and fear thousands
of jobs are at risk in the long term.
The move comes in spite of the unions' continuing difficulties in forming a
European works council at Ford, designed to give a collective voice to
workers from all six European countries where Ford has a presence.
German union leaders want Euro-works council representatives to be elected
from Ford employees only. The British want some full-time union officials on
the proposed 20-member council.
This week, however, negotiators from Britain, Germany, Belgium, Spain and
Portugal will ask Ford of Europe management for a meeting to request
assurances that no core processes will be sub-contracted within the next
five years. They also agreed to contact the US Union of Auto Workers for
more information.
Unions believe the proposal to put seat production at Ford in Britain out to
tender will lead to 800 job losses and heralds a move to increase
sub-contracting. Ford is due to decide on that proposal later this year.
Ford has little choice but to buy in more component systems and processes
from outside suppliers if it is to remain competitive with the leading
Japanese vehicle makers on costs.
On average more than 60 per cent of the value of Japanese vehicles is made
up of externally supplied components.
Western carmakers, like their Japanese counterparts, can cut costs
substantially by forging long-term partnerships with a relatively small
number of key suppliers. These suppliers are required to bear all the big
costs of research and development in exchange for long-term supply
contracts.
Mr Jack Adams, deputy general secretary of the TGWU general union who
attended a meeting of all Ford European unions in Geneva this month, said:
'Ford unions without exception do not agree to out-sourcing without
negotiations and agreement on items to be out-sourced.'
Ford denied that it plans to sub-contract core businesses. The company said:
'Out-sourcing of some work is an on-going process. We have looked at
peripheral areas for a number of years. We are always asking whether someone
can do the work better than we can.'
It added that any substantial increase in sub-contracting would be a matter
for long-term discussion with unions.
European Community trade unions have united with employers' organisations in
an appeal for governments to support a co-operative growth strategy for more
employment.
The two sides have called for the rapid reduction of interest rates in an
eight-point statement timed to coincide with a meeting of EC finance
ministers today.
ENGINEERS at Ford's research and development plant in Dunton, Essex, are to
stage a one-day strike tomorrow in protest over the company's plan to
relocate 300 jobs to Germany.
Members of the MSF technical union voted almost two to one in favour of the
action which will be the third stoppage in the dispute that began in May.
The relocation is part of the company's strategy of 'co-location' that
involves bringing together staff working on similar activities. The company
has said nobody will be forced to move to Germany, and that with the
co-operation of employees compulsory redundancies can be avoided.
Ford believes that the current multi-site structure of its technical
operations puts it at a competitive disadvantage. It plans to consolidate
technical operations into two sites in Europe, one in Britain and one in
Germany.
</TEXT>
