<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 92 / Survey case may go to Lords
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDEPENDENT INSURANCE, an insurer that provides professional indemnity
cover, may petition the House of Lords after losing a landmark court case
over the supervision required for trainee surveyors.
The Court of Appeal last week overturned a ruling that an unqualified
surveyor always needed on-site supervision from a professional to validate
the terms of the surveyor's professional indemnity cover.
Independent had won a judgment in June last year under Judge Fox Andrews in
the official Referee Users Court, which is widely used by the construction
industry, against Congrave Horner, a firm of chartered surveyors.
The case arose after a trainee surveyor with Congrave Horner failed to
discover the extent of dry rot in a house. The firm paid more than Pounds
100,000 in compensation to the house owners, but Independent, its insurer,
refused to pay up on its policy.
Judge Fox Andrews backed Independent, ruling that attendance by a qualified
surveyor was required at each of four stages of the survey: preparation,
visual inspection, evaluation, and the final report. The trainee had been
supervised only at the final stage.
The Court of Appeal ruled in favour of Congrave Horner, arguing that the
level of supervision required would vary according to how skilled and near
to qualification the trainee was. It also said that the terms of supervision
were very vaguely drawn up.
Mr Keith Rutter, Independent's assistant general manager, said: 'Our view is
that we have a valid case. We maintain that view. We may well seek a
petition for leave to appeal.'
He added: 'I've been doing this too long to get disappointed about losing
court cases.'
</TEXT>
