FT  13 JUL 92 / Housebuilders warn Lamont of crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of Britain's larger housebuilders are expected this week to write to
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to warn him of the deepening crisis in the
industry.
The group, which is thought to contain most of the 20 largest housebuilders,
is concerned at the continuing low level of sales, which they say are
impeding recovery in prices. These have fallen on average by between 25 per
cent and 30 per cent in southern England and East Anglia since the end of
1988.
The largest companies are also considering seeking a meeting with Mr John
Major, the prime minister, so grave do they believe conditions have become
in the construction industry generally.
The letter to the chancellor is expected to urge the government to take
measures to stimulate the economy, which many builders fear is moving from
recession to slump. It is also likely to raise concern over people trapped
in homes that are now worth less than the mortgages raised to pay for them.
Builders are also unhappy at the Treasury decision to reimpose stamp duty
next month on house purchases under Pounds 250,000. They regard the move as
unhelpful at this point in the housing market.
They say that sales have become increasingly difficult during recent months,
in spite of the outcome of the general election which had been expected to
encourage greater confidence among purchasers by the removal of political
uncertainty.
Instead, sales have continued to languish during what is normally one of the
busiest selling periods of the year, before the school summer holidays.
</TEXT>
