<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 92 / MMC may judge BT and Oftel price row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LACK of progress in talks between British Telecommunications and Oftel, its
regulator, over a tighter price-control regime means that the issue could be
referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
One consequence of the dispute is that BT is delaying the announcement of
more than Pounds 100m in price cuts scheduled for the autumn. It is
concerned not to make price changes this year that would have to be reversed
next year.
When Oftel unveiled its new pricing scheme last month, it gave BT until the
end of the month to accept it.
Not only has that deadline lapsed, but the most recent talks between the two
sides last Thursday have been described as 'frosty'. Both sides, which only
a week ago expected to reach an agreement, now talk privately about the
possibility of referring the matter to the MMC, which has the power to
impose a solution.
However, given that BT and Oftel have threatened to go to the MMC several
times in the past, the present dispute seems to point to the two sides'
tough negotiating stances rather than a total breakdown of talks.
Oftel, which is being led by Mr Bill Wigglesworth in an interim capacity
following the departure of Sir Bryan Carsberg to the Office of Fair Trading
last month, is sticking to the line that its new regime is not up for
negotiation.
Oftel has told BT to agree to cut the price of a basket of its basic
services each year by inflation minus 7.5 percentage points, compared with
6.25 points at present. The company has also been told to make sure small
retail customers share in the price cuts.
BT, whose negotiations are led by Mr Jonathan Rickford, government relations
director, seems to have accepted that Oftel will not change the main
elements of the regime, but hopes that detailed matters of interpretation
can be resolved in its favour. 'The devil is in the details,' a BT executive
said.
Oftel's new regime would require BT to cut connection charges sharply. If
the company agrees to do this, it might make sense to start the process this
year instead of continuing its practice of increasing connection charges.
Another issue concerns special discounts for businesses and heavy
residential users of the phone, which at the moment count towards the
overall price cuts BT must make. They would not, under the new regime,
meaning BT might have an incentive to introduce more generous discounts this
year before the regime is changed.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
