   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH is set for a crushing victory over Mr Bryan Gould in this
week's Labour leadership contest with the support of up to 90 per cent of
the party's electorate, Philip Stephens writes.
The shadow chancellor's campaign advisers predicted yesterday that his
overwhelming support in all three branches of the electoral college that
chooses the leader - the unions, parliamentary party and constituencies -
would give him unprecedented authority as leader. In 1983 Mr Neil Kinnock
secured 71 per cent of the vote.
Mrs Margaret Beckett is expected to beat off comfortably challenges from Mr
John Prescott and Mr Gould when the votes in the deputy and the leadership
contest are counted on Saturday. Her team is confident that she is already
assured of well over 50 per cent of the vote. Mr Prescott is expected to win
second place, with Mr Gould trailing in third.
Mr Gould's team yesterday conceded defeat in both contests with a call for
the new party leadership to acknowledge the role he had played in ensuring
the 'genuine' choice of leaders. Mr David Blunkett, who has led the Gould
campaign, said that once the result was announced the candidates should put
behind them the 'harsh words' spoken during the campaign and Mr Gould should
be given a 'major role' in the leadership team.
Mr Smith's aides indicated that there would be no attempt to 'punish' the
challenger by giving him a low-profile post in the new shadow cabinet.
