<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 92 / BR will continue to run railways until end of century
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL will continue to run the railways to the end of the decade and
beyond under the government's substantially watered-down plans for
privatisation to be set out in a white paper tomorrow.
The slow-track approach will be greeted with relief by BR, but will come as
a bitter disappointment to Tory backbenchers and others who had hoped to see
a more radical shake-up and sale of the corporation.
Although BR's stations are to be put up for sale, ministers acknowledge that
only a minority of BR's passenger train services are likely to find their
way into the hands of the private sector in the foreseeable future.
They are pinning their hopes on the possibility that this small number of
privately-operated services will set an example that embarrasses BR into
doing better.
The latest plans will leave BR in charge of the railway tracks indefinitely.
Privatisation will consist mainly of trying to get the private sector to run
the trains.
However, only freight trains will be offered for outright sale. On the
passenger side, the private sector's role will be limited mainly to
operating some routes under franchise.
The government is likely to proceed extremely cautiously with the award of
franchises because of the private sector's lack of previous experience
operating complex railway services.
The private sector is also wary of the opportunities because of
uncertainties over whether there is any money to be made from running
trains. It has not been reassured by the escalating losses reported by BR
two weeks ago.
The white paper will attempt to ease some of the private sector's anxieties
about costs by allowing franchisees to lease passenger trains from BR
instead of buying their own.
If a franchise is not renewed, BR will guarantee to take the trains back
from franchisees. This will considerably reduce the risks to the private
sector in taking on a franchise.
In addition to privatising BR's existing services, the white paper will
allow would-be operators to start up new services alongside BR's. Several
companies such as Virgin Atlantic, the airline, have expressed an interest
in doing so.
However, this is unlikely to produce large numbers of additional passenger
services because operators will need to secure access to BR's tracks, many
of which have little or no spare capacity.
Not quite running like clockwork, Page 6
</TEXT>
