<TEXT>
Minoru Murofushi, the 61-year-old chief executive of C Itoh, one of the
world's biggest trading houses, has been appointed to the board of HSBC
Holdings, the new owner of Midland Bank.
This is believed to be the first time that HSBC, parent of the Hongkong
Bank, has put a Japanese businessman on its board and is in line with the
group's plans to give it a more international flavour. Until now it has been
dominated by local Hong Kong businessmen.
Murofushi joined C Itoh in 1956 after graduating in law from Tokyo
University. In 1963 he was made general manager of the group's coal
department in New York and became vice president of C Itoh (America) in
1971. He went on the board of C Itoh in 1985 and was appointed chief
executive in June 1990.
